  "response_text": "**Trie Implementation**\n======================\n\nA trie, also known as a prefix tree, is a tree-like data structure in which every node is associated with a string. It is often used to store a dynamic set or associative array where the keys are usually strings.\n\n### Trie Node Class\n\n```python\nclass TrieNode:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.children = {}  # Dictionary to store child nodes\n        self.is_end_of_word = False  # Flag to indicate the end of a word\n```\n\n### Trie Class\n\n```python\nclass Trie:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.root = TrieNode()  # Initialize the root node\n\n    def insert(self, word):\n        \"\"\"\n        Insert a word into the trie.\n        \n        Args:\n            word (str): The word to be inserted.\n        \"\"\"\n        node = self.root\n        for char in word:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                node.children[char] = TrieNode()\n            node = node.children[char]\n        node.is_end_of_word = True\n\n    def search(self, word):\n        \"\"\"\n        Search for a word in the trie.\n        \n        Args:\n            word (str): The word to be searched.\n        \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if the word is found, False otherwise.\n        \"\"\"\n        node = self.root\n        for char in word:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                return False\n            node = node.children[char]\n        return node.is_end_of_word\n\n    def starts_with(self, prefix):\n        \"\"\"\n        Check if there is any word in the trie that starts with the given prefix.\n        \n        Args:\n            prefix (str): The prefix to be searched.\n        \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if there is a word that starts with the prefix, False otherwise.\n        \"\"\"\n        node = self.root\n        for char in prefix:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                return False\n            node = node.children[char]\n        return True\n\n    def delete(self, word):\n        \"\"\"\n        Delete a word from the trie.\n        \n        Args:\n            word (str): The word to be deleted.\n        \"\"\"\n        def _delete(node, word, index):\n            if index == len(word):\n                if not node.is_end_of_word:\n                    return False\n                node.is_end_of_word = False\n                return len(node.children) == 0\n            char = word[index]\n            if char not in node.children:\n                return False\n            should_delete_current_node = _delete(node.children[char], word, index + 1)\n            if should_delete_current_node:\n                del node.children[char]\n                return len(node.children) == 0\n            return False\n\n        _delete(self.root, word, 0)\n```\n\n### When is a Trie more efficient than a Hash Table?\n\nA trie is more efficient than a hash table in the following scenarios:\n\n1.  **Prefix matching",
